initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.
stories: Unbiased triangles serve as crucial feature indicators in stability diagrams of quantum dot (QD) devices within the realm of spin physics. However, limitations in data quality and accessibility, coupled with the intricacy of pertinent physical phenomena, have impeded the development of an automated and customized analysis framework. In response, we propose an unsupervised feature extraction framework for bias triangles, employing computer vision techniques based on segmentation. This methodology allows for the straightforward identification and measurement of the triangles' physical attributes. By circumventing the necessity for human input or extensive training datasets, we enable the automation of pixel-level shape and feature labeling. Moreover, we showcase the effectiveness, efficiency, and training-data-free detection of Pauli spin blockade (PSB) through this approach.

Triangles free from bias serve as vital signs in quantum dot (QD) devices' stability diagrams, significant in the sphere of spin physics. Yet, constraints in data precision and availability, in addition to the complexity of related physical processes, have obstructed the establishment of a sophisticated and tailored analysis system. To address this challenge, we suggest an unsupervised feature extraction method for bias triangles, utilizing computer vision approaches centered around segmentation. This approach permits the easy recognition and quantification of the triangles' fundamental properties. By eliminating the requirement for human intervention or extensive instructional datasets, we facilitate the automation of pixel-level shape and trait classification. Furthermore, we demonstrate the capability, expediency, and data-independent detection of Pauli spin blockade (PSB) through this strategy.
